hnhlt of thrift: they\nare buying, true, but they nro elim\ninating In their buying tlt super\nabundance, of luxuries that charac\nterised It recently nnd are putting\ntnnney Into tho bank Hanks every\nwhere, Mr Moran siys, tell him thnt\np.ople who never did pitch n thing\nIn their lives before are Martini? sav\nInpt accounts nnd this on less\ntnnney In the proceed of scaling down\nthan that out of which they were\nunable, apparently, to nave nt.ull be\nfore. nig ltnslncss In Sight.\nThis new national habit of thrift,\n(oinblned with the action of the fed\niral reserve hoard enabling the\nhanks to establish themselves moro\nfirmly upon n basis of normal rate\nof supply nnd lemnnd, means busi\nness on a larger scalo than over bo\nfore. Mr Mornn, believes. Another\nhopeful sign brought to his ntten\ntlon during his tour Is tho fact that\njrood banks nro consolidating now to\nu much creator extent than before,\nThu railroads, being the nrtcrles\nof commerce of thn country, uro so\nrliis-ly Interwoven with Its welfare\nthat their prosperity or their dln\nrouragemcnt is bound to be tho com\nmon prosperity or tho common de\npression of all, Mr. Moran wild, .hut\nhe believes that readjustment entail\ning tho reduction of operating ex\npenses and scaling down In propor\ntion to tho present cost of living,\nwill bo accomplished In n compara\ntively short tlmo and wl;h Httlo\ntrouble.\nSees Crude Coming llnrk.\nIlecause thn cut in crude oil thnt\nbrought to bear upon Oklalioma\nbusiness and finance tho same tem\nporary depression that has been felt\nfor sninn months in thn manufactur\ning and farming districts of tho mid\ndie west and east came late, Okla\nhoma will recover oomparntlvoly\nsooner, Mr. Mornn believes, nnd ho\nis looking for 13 oil again within tho\nnext two or three months.\nThe fact that Kurnpo Is debtor to\nthe United States, hn said, Including\ngovernment, municipal nnd prlvato\nloans, to tho extent of some $20,\n000,000,000 and that this country\nholds tho